Tutorial

Doing DevOps with GitHub

5 steps

In the previous tutorial, you installed and explored GitHub Desktop and its basic Git features. Now that you have some experience using GitHub Desktop, it’s time to go through some common development practices with GitHub. In this tutorial, you will be creating a static website and hosting it with GitHub pages, while implementing branch protection and merge reviews for moving code from development to production.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • There are no pre-requisites

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  • Configure branch protection rules
  • Create a pull request
  • Approve and merge a pull request
  • Configure GitHub Pages

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 5

  • Step 1: Project Introduction

    Imagine that you are working in a software development company that has been contracted by a fast food restaurant to develop their website. Your first deliverable is a product page for one of the restaurant's bestsellers, the Big Burger. As the lead developer for the project, your task is to create a suitable collaborative development environment for your team, setting appropriate security and DevOps measures in place.

    Using GitHub, your team aims to make us of a development environment with a structure as laid out in this diagram:

  • Step 2: Creating a New Repository

    As this tutorial requires you to use a program downloaded in the previous tutorial, please complete it before attempting this tutorial.

    To start, just like you did in the previous tutorial, create and publish a new repository named “Username-Git Shop”. You should replace “Username” with your StackUp username. E.g. if your username is Stackie1234, your repository should be named Stackie1234-Git Shop.

    When creating the repository, make sure the “Keep code private” option is left unchecked.

    Then, create a branch named “development” and publish it. Switch to this branch.

    Next, create a file named index.html in the root directory of your repository. Enter the following HTML code into the file. This code creates the structure for a basic product page for a shop website that will be hosted later on.

    <!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
   <title>Username-Git Shop</title>
   <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
   <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">
   <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin>
   <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Poppins&display=swap" rel="stylesheet"> </head> 
<body>
   <div class="nav">
     <a href="#" class="logo">Username Shop</a>
     <a href="#">Home</a>
     <a href="#">About</a>
     <a href="#">Contact</a>
   </div>
   <div class="content">
     <div class="container">
       <div>
         <img src="https://cdn-icons-png.flaticon.com/512/2674/2674087.png">
       </div>
       <div>
         <h2>Big Burger</h2>
         <p>Just a very big burger</p>
         <p>Price: $10</p>
         <button>Add to cart</button>
       </div>
     </div>
   </div>
   <div class="footer">
     <a href="https://www.flaticon.com/free-icons/burger" title="burger icons">Burger icons created by Freepik - Flaticon</a>
   </div>
 </body>
 </html>

    IMPORTANT: Remember to replace all instances of "Username" in the code with your own username!

    Also create a file named style.css with the following code to define the styles that should be applied to the HTML structures you created earlier.

    * {

    Proceed to commit and push the new code to the development branch.

    Expected Output

  • Step 3: Creating a Branch Protection Rule

    Branch Protection Rules are rules that apply to branches in your repository to protect them from unapproved or direct changes. This is important in actual development as you wouldn't want changes to be made to the main branch without reviews from those who are in charge of the project as it could lead to problematic changes being deployed.

    To set branch protection rules, follow the steps below:

    1. First, head over to the settings for your Username-Git Shop repository on github.com and click on “Branches” under “Code and automation”.
    2. Then, click “Add rule” in the “Branch protection rules” section. Set the branch name pattern to your “main” branch.
    3. Enable “Require a pull request before merging” and “Require approvals” within that section, and “Require status checks to pass before merging”.
    4. Finally, click on “Create”.

    Check out 'Expected Output' if you want additional confirmation of what this should look like.

    Expected Output

  • Step 4: Configuring GitHub Pages

    Since we want to host the Big Burger product page on GitHub, we’ll need to configure GitHub Pages to allow this. While you’re less likely to host a company’s website on Pages, we are introducing this option to you in this quest as Pages can be useful for developers looking for options to host their own personal portfolios.

    To configure GitHub Pages:

    1. In the Settings page for your repository, under “Code and automation”, click on “Pages”.
    2. Select “Deploy from a branch” as your source and “main” as the branch to deploy. This step deploys your static code in the “main” branch and makes it visible online at your GitHub domain.

    Check out 'Expected Output' if you want additional confirmation of what this should look like.

    Configuring GitHub Pages makes your Big Burger website available at the URL https://YourGitHubUsername.github.io/Username-Git-Shop/, where YourGitHubUsername. in the link is replaced by your own username on GitHub.

    Expected Output

  • Step 5: Moving from Development to Production

    Currently, if you head to https://YourGitHubUsername.github.io/Username-Git-Shop/ with the appropriate parts of the URL replaced, you will notice that your website does not show the contents of the HTML code that you pushed in Step 1. This is because the code is still in the development branch, while GitHub is hosting the contents of the “main” branch.

    To move your code from development to production, open GitHub Desktop to the “Changes” tab. You should see a “Create Pull Request” button. Pull Requests are requests to merge two branches that you specify, which would usually be reviewed by senior developers and approved, before being merged.

    Clicking the button should bring you to github.com, to a page that looks like the one below.

    On this page, you may choose to change the title and add comments. Typically, when opening a pull request, developers would enter the changes to the code that they had made on the branch. This allows the person(s) reviewing the pull request to know what the new code does and what to look out for.

    Once you’re done, click “Create pull request” to create a pull request to merge the changes in the “development” branch into the “main” branch.

    Typically, at this point in the process, you would have collaborators or senior developers who would review your code changes to ensure that the code is relevant and bug free, before merging the pull request. This ensures that no faulty or unintended code, which could cause issues, gets deployed or pushed to the main branch.

    For this tutorial, you will merge your own pull request. After creating the pull request above, you should see a screen that looks like this.

    Select “Merge without waiting for requirements to be met (bypass branch protections), and lastly click on “Merge pull request” and “Confirm merge”.

    Once your pull request is successfully merged, you’ll see your code changes pushed into the “main” branch. If configured correctly, you should also be able to see your website at YourGitHubUsername.github.io/Username-Git-Shop/ (replace YourGitHubUsername and Username with your StackUp username). You may have to wait a few minutes and refresh your page before it appears.

    Congratulations! You've managed different versions of code by merging your first pull request. Once you're ready, head onto the next tutorial to learn how to perform CI/CD actions with GitHub.
